WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.600
Hey y'all, I'm JP.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:08.600
And I'm Sarah.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:13.320
And we are PhD students at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:16.520
As you can imagine, in North Carolina, there's a lot of different farmer's market.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:20.879
The Carrboro farmer's market is two minutes away from where I live.

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:25.559
Now I go here every Saturday, and what I've learned is the food just tastes so much better

00:00:25.559 --> 00:00:30.320
when you get to know the farmer.

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:34.720
JP recently took me to my first farmer's market, and there it was a lot of fun, but it was

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:36.599
really overwhelming at first.

00:00:36.599 --> 00:00:40.799
Because there was so much going on, I didn't know who to talk to, or what to say, or even

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:42.139
where to start.

00:00:42.139 --> 00:00:47.060
And this reminded me a lot of when I started coding in R. I was faced with this beautiful

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:54.200
wall of hex codes, but I wasn't sure how they worked, or where to start, or what to do once

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:56.240
I loaded a package.

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:01.439
It wasn't until recently that I realized behind each of these packages is a person that really

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:07.440
wants you to succeed in using that package, even though it can be a little bit intimidating

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.559
still to reach out to these people and know what to say.

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:16.320
So I've had some success doing this on my podcast, From Where Does It Stem?, where I

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:19.760
interview scientists from all over the world and ask them how they got there.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:23.879
I've interviewed people like Jane Goodall, the director of the NIH, Francis Collins,

00:01:23.879 --> 00:01:28.480
Tony Fauci's boss, and our boy, Hadley Wickham.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:32.199
I asked them questions about their upbringings, how they got to where they are, what their

00:01:32.199 --> 00:01:38.540
favorite songs are, and also how they think STEM or science can be more inclusive.

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:43.360
So for this year's Posit Conference, we decided to ask some local R slash bioconductor celebrities

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:44.720
some questions.

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.139
We did video interviews with two of them to give you an idea of how these conversations

00:01:48.139 --> 00:01:49.139
might go.

00:01:49.139 --> 00:01:51.720
Joe and Winston, if you're here, I'd turn around if you don't like seeing yourself on

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:53.519
the big screen.

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:57.559
So hey, big Winston and Joe, tell us about the Posit community.

00:01:57.559 --> 00:02:03.279
It is really nice to be in a community where there's a lot of people coming from a lot

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:05.760
of different places and everyone gets along.

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:12.559
In terms of inclusiveness, that is something that was very intentional.

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:17.559
There's also other users groups out there, like Our Ladies.

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:20.479
Those things just sort of developed organically.

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:22.759
People involved in that did a really great job.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:30.520
Every time I have an interaction with someone who not only has appreciation for what the

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:37.000
software does, but what it's allowed them to do or to become as a person, and especially

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:44.880
if that person feels like this is a space that they didn't necessarily feel like they

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:52.080
might be welcomed, it is just incredibly motivating for me and for us to go out and do our best

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:55.559
work year after year.

00:02:55.559 --> 00:02:57.039
Winston has his head down over there.

00:02:57.039 --> 00:02:59.679
All right, cool, cool, cool.

00:02:59.679 --> 00:03:03.119
Winston and Joe, what are some things you do outside of package development?

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:07.839
In periods in the past, I've done photography pretty intensely.

00:03:07.839 --> 00:03:10.839
I also do some woodworking.

00:03:10.839 --> 00:03:13.479
I love cycling.

00:03:13.479 --> 00:03:18.399
I don't get to do it as much as I would like to, but it's definitely a nice antidote to,

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:26.759
I feel like I cram my brain full at work and then cycling lets me sort of release.

00:03:26.759 --> 00:03:28.160
And on a great smile.

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:29.160
Yes.

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:31.720
And thanks again to you guys for talking to us.

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:36.759
And we found everyone we reached out to was really receptive to just chatting and answering

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:41.160
questions about their life and what they do outside of coding.

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:44.320
But the Pawsit community is so much more than just these developers.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:48.479
It also involves everyone in this room and everyone watching this video.

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:53.639
I found the strongest connection through joining my lab with two graduate students there at

00:03:53.639 --> 00:03:55.399
the time, Nicole and Eric.

00:03:55.399 --> 00:03:59.360
They now have their PhDs and are off doing wonderful things, but at the time, they were

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:04.039
developing their own R packages to do some biological research.

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:09.080
So I got hands-on experience and got to contribute to these packages, and not only am I extremely

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:14.600
lucky to call these guys my friends, but they also let me have the confidence to create

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:18.279
my own package, which is under development.

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:22.959
If you don't have your own team of people that you can meet with every day, there are

00:04:22.959 --> 00:04:26.959
some great resources through the Pawsit community and their website as well.

00:04:26.959 --> 00:04:31.320
Things like coming to this conference or checking out their YouTube channel, going to data science

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:35.799
hangouts and commenting there and being a part of it, or joining one of these user groups

00:04:35.839 --> 00:04:39.160
like R-Ladies or the R for data science learning community.

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:42.040
Yeah, we got some representation here.

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:45.200
And the R for data science community also runs the Tidy Tuesday if you've ever done

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:47.799
that or want to challenge yourself with it.

00:04:47.799 --> 00:04:54.079
So hopefully we have planted a seed today to inspire you to connect with the community

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:59.040
and the people around you and use those connections to challenge yourself to do something outside

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:03.679
your comfort zone to give you the confidence to create something new, whether it be a package,

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:07.040
a workflow, or your own unique project.

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:09.760
If you're interested in checking out the podcast, here's a Spotify code.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:12.359
If you want to reach out to Sarah and I, please do.

00:05:12.359 --> 00:05:13.359
Here are our emails.

00:05:13.359 --> 00:05:15.799
We'd love to interview some people for the podcast.

00:05:15.799 --> 00:05:19.920
And for Yi Hui's interview and Mike Love's, feel free to scan this QR code.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:20.920
Thank you.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:21.420
Thank you.

